% ─── Abstract ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
\begin{abstract}
\noindent
This report presents \textbf{ChaatCheck}, an end-to-end deep learning application for recognising 12 categories of Indian street food from photographs. We fine-tune a MobileNetV2 backbone pre-trained on ImageNet using a two-stage transfer learning strategy: first training only the classifier head on frozen convolutional features, then partially unfreezing the last three convolutional blocks for domain adaptation. The model is trained on 1,260 images (50 original per class, augmented 3$\times$ with random flips, rotations, and colour jitter) and evaluated on a held-out test set of 96 images, achieving a test accuracy of \textbf{83.33\%} with a macro F1-score of \textbf{0.81}. Per-class analysis reveals that visually distinctive dishes (e.g., jalebi, F1 = 1.00) are classified near-perfectly, while visually similar fried items (e.g., daal\_puri, F1 = 0.33) remain challenging. The trained model is deployed via a Streamlit web application that provides real-time predictions alongside estimated calorie counts, dietary labels, ingredient lists, and colour-coded allergen warnings.
\end{abstract}
