\section{Model Architecture}
% ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

\subsection{Base Model — MobileNetV2}

MobileNetV2~\cite{mobilenetv2} was selected over heavier alternatives (e.g., ResNet-50 at $\approx$25M parameters) for its strong accuracy-to-parameter ratio ($\approx$3.4M parameters), making it well-suited for real-time inference in a lightweight Streamlit deployment. The architecture introduces two key innovations:

\subsubsection{Depthwise Separable Convolutions}

Standard convolutions apply a $k \times k$ filter across \textit{all} input channels simultaneously, requiring $k^2 \cdot C_{\text{in}} \cdot C_{\text{out}}$ multiplications per spatial position. MobileNetV2 factorises this into two steps:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item \textbf{Depthwise convolution} — a single $k \times k$ filter per input channel ($k^2 \cdot C_{\text{in}}$ operations).
  \item \textbf{Pointwise convolution} — a $1 \times 1$ convolution to mix channels ($C_{\text{in}} \cdot C_{\text{out}}$ operations).
\end{enumerate}

\noindent This reduces computation by a factor of approximately $\frac{1}{C_{\text{out}}} + \frac{1}{k^2}$, which for $k=3$ and $C_{\text{out}} = 32$ yields a $\sim$8--9$\times$ speedup over standard convolutions.

\subsubsection{Inverted Residual Blocks with Linear Bottlenecks}

Unlike ResNet's bottleneck (which \textit{compresses} to a lower dimension, processes, then \textit{expands}), MobileNetV2's inverted residual blocks do the opposite: they \textbf{expand} the channel dimension via a $1 \times 1$ convolution (expansion factor $t = 6$), apply a depthwise $3 \times 3$ convolution in the expanded space, then \textbf{project back} to a narrow bottleneck. Residual connections are added between the narrow bottleneck layers.

Crucially, the final projection uses a \textbf{linear activation} (no ReLU) because ReLU destroys information in low-dimensional spaces — a key insight from the MobileNetV2 paper that preserves representational capacity in the bottleneck.

