\subsection{Hyperparameter Rationale}

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item \textbf{Adam optimiser} was chosen over SGD because Adam's per-parameter adaptive learning rates are well-suited for fine-tuning scenarios where the classifier head (randomly initialised) and the backbone (pre-trained) have very different gradient magnitudes. Adam converges faster on small datasets where SGD's momentum-based updates may oscillate.
  \item \textbf{CrossEntropyLoss} combines \texttt{LogSoftmax} and \texttt{NLLLoss} into a single numerically stable operation, and is the standard choice for multi-class classification with mutually exclusive labels.
  \item \textbf{Batch size 32} balances GPU memory utilisation (Google Colab T4 with 15 GB VRAM) with sufficient gradient noise to aid generalisation on a small dataset. Larger batches (64, 128) risk memorising the limited training data.
  \item \textbf{Learning rate ($10^{-3}$ for Stage 1, $10^{-4}$ for Stage 2):} The 10$\times$ reduction in Stage 2 ensures that the unfrozen convolutional layers are updated gently, preserving the useful ImageNet features while allowing domain-specific adaptation.
\end{itemize}

