\subsubsection{Key Observations}

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item \textbf{Best performer:} \textit{jalebi} achieves a perfect F1-score of 1.00. Its distinctive bright orange colour and spiral shape make it visually unambiguous.
  \item \textbf{Worst performer:} \textit{daal\_puri} (F1 = 0.33) is frequently confused with \textit{bhatura} (2 misclassifications), \textit{kachori} (2), and \textit{poha} (1). All three are visually similar deep-fried items with comparable colour and texture.
  \item \textbf{Low recall:} \textit{litti\_chokha} has perfect precision (1.00) but very low recall (0.43) — the model correctly identifies it when it predicts it, but fails to recognise 4 out of 7 samples, misclassifying them across 4 different classes.
  \item \textbf{Pattern:} Classes with unique visual signatures (jalebi, poha, unni\_appam) perform best, while classes sharing a ``fried dough'' appearance (daal\_puri, kachori, bhatura) show the most cross-confusion.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Confusion Matrix}

Figure~\ref{fig:confmatrix} shows the full $12 \times 12$ confusion matrix on the validation set. The strong diagonal confirms that most classes are well-separated. The most notable off-diagonal cluster is in the \textit{daal\_puri} row, where misclassifications are spread across \textit{bhatura} (2), \textit{kachori} (2), and \textit{poha} (1) — all visually similar items.

