    \label{fig:confmatrix}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Error Analysis}

A closer inspection of the confusion matrix (Figure~\ref{fig:confmatrix}) and the per-class metrics (Table~\ref{tab:classreport}) reveals three distinct failure modes:

\subsubsection{Failure Mode 1: The Fried-Dough Cluster}

\textit{daal\_puri}, \textit{kachori}, and \textit{bhatura} form a confusion cluster. All three are deep-fried, wheat-based items with similar golden-brown colour and round shape. Specifically:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item Of 7 \textit{daal\_puri} samples, only 2 were correctly classified. Two were predicted as \textit{bhatura}, two as \textit{kachori}, and one as \textit{poha}.
  \item Of 7 \textit{kachori} samples, 2 were misclassified as \textit{daal\_puri} — confirming a bidirectional confusion between these two classes.
\end{itemize}

\noindent This suggests that the convolutional features extracted by MobileNetV2 struggle to distinguish fine-grained textural differences (e.g., stuffing visibility, surface crispness) within the fried-dough category. A possible remedy is to increase the training data for these classes or apply more aggressive augmentation (e.g., random cropping to expose internal texture).

\subsubsection{Failure Mode 2: High Variance in Plating (litti\_chokha)}

\textit{litti\_chokha} has perfect precision (1.00) but the lowest recall of any class (0.43). The 4 misclassified samples were spread across \textit{chana\_masala} (1), \textit{kachori} (1), \textit{kuzhi\_paniyaram} (1), and \textit{unni\_appam} (1) — no single dominant confusion target.

This scatter pattern indicates that the issue is not similarity to one particular class, but rather \textbf{high intra-class visual variance}: litti\_chokha is presented with varying accompaniments (chokha, chutney, daal), different plating styles, and sometimes with the litti cut open vs. whole. With only 35 original training images (105 after augmentation), the model has not learned to generalise across these presentation variants.

\subsubsection{Failure Mode 3: Well-Separated Classes}

Six classes achieve F1 $\geq$ 0.88: \textit{jalebi} (1.00), \textit{chana\_masala} (0.93), \textit{poha} (0.93), \textit{aloo\_tikki} (0.92), \textit{rabri} (0.92), and \textit{bhatura} (0.88). These classes share a common trait: \textbf{distinctive visual signatures} — jalebi's spiral shape, poha's flattened rice texture, rabri's creamy white appearance, and chana\_masala's characteristic chickpea-and-gravy look. Transfer learning from ImageNet is most effective when target classes have clearly separable visual features, which these classes provide.

