\section{Limitations \& Future Work}
% ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

\subsection{Current Limitations}

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item \textbf{Small dataset (50 images/class):} The original dataset contains only 50 images per class, expanded to 105 per class after augmentation. This leads to two measurable effects:
  \begin{itemize}
    \item \textit{daal\_puri} achieves only F1 = 0.33 (worst of all 12 classes), partly because 35 training images are insufficient to capture the visual diversity of stuffed fried breads.
    \item \textit{litti\_chokha} achieves only F1 = 0.60 despite perfect precision, indicating the model has not seen enough plating variations.
  \end{itemize}

  \item \textbf{Validation oscillation ($\pm$3.5\%):} Validation accuracy fluctuates between 79.76\% and 83.33\% across epochs (a range of 3.57 percentage points), caused by the small validation set of only 7 images per class — a single misclassification changes accuracy by 1.19\%.

  \item \textbf{Missing ImageNet normalisation:} Neither the training transforms nor the inference transform apply the standard ImageNet normalisation (mean = $[0.485, 0.456, 0.406]$, std = $[0.229, 0.224, 0.225]$). While this is \textit{internally consistent} (training and inference match), it means the pre-trained MobileNetV2 features receive inputs on a different scale than they were originally trained on, potentially reducing transfer learning effectiveness.

  \item \textbf{Static metadata:} Calorie estimates and allergen information are hard-coded as a Python dictionary rather than queried from a structured nutrition database such as the IFCT 2017~\cite{ifct}.

  \item \textbf{No learning rate scheduler:} A fixed learning rate throughout training contributes to the validation oscillation. Adaptive scheduling (e.g., \texttt{ReduceLROnPlateau}) would allow the optimiser to take smaller steps as it approaches convergence.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Proposed Improvements}

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item \textbf{Expand dataset to 200+ images/class:} Scrape additional images from food blogs, Google Images, or the Indian Food 101 dataset~\cite{indianfood101}. Prioritise the weakest classes (daal\_puri, litti\_chokha, kachori) for targeted data collection.
  \item \textbf{Add ImageNet normalisation:} Add \texttt{Normalize(mean=[0.485, 0.456, 0.406], std=[0.229, 0.224, 0.225])} to both training and inference transforms. Based on literature, this alone can improve accuracy by 3--5\% for ImageNet-pretrained backbones.
  \item \textbf{Learning rate scheduler:} Use \texttt{CosineAnnealingLR} or \texttt{ReduceLROnPlateau} to reduce the learning rate as training plateaus, reducing the observed validation oscillation.
  \item \textbf{Class-specific augmentation:} Apply heavier augmentation (random cropping, cutout, Mixup) specifically to the visually ambiguous fried-dough classes to improve intra-class diversity.
  \item \textbf{Expand to Tier 2 / Tier 3:} Scale from 12 to 30 or all 80 classes using progressive training and curriculum learning.
  \item \textbf{Mobile deployment:} Export to ONNX or TorchScript for real-time on-device inference on smartphones.
\end{enumerate}

