\section{Conclusion}
% ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

The \textbf{ChaatCheck} project successfully demonstrates the viability of lightweight convolutional neural networks for fine-grained cultural food recognition. By applying a two-stage transfer learning strategy to a MobileNetV2 backbone, we mitigated the risks of catastrophic forgetting and effectively adapted ImageNet features to the visually complex domain of Indian street food. Despite the constraints of a highly restricted dataset (only 50 original images per class), the application of strategic offline augmentation and careful hyperparameter tuning yielded a robust model capable of \textbf{83.33\% test accuracy} and a \textbf{0.81 macro F1-score}. 

Crucially, the project extends beyond a mere classification exercise by deploying the trained model via a responsive Streamlit web application. By coupling high-speed inference ($<$100ms on CPU) with a curated metadata dictionary, the system provides immediate, actionable nutritional and allergen intelligence. This end-to-end pipeline—from automated data acquisition and augmentation to model training and interactive deployment—establishes a scalable, reproducible foundation for culturally-aware dietary tracking and food safety applications.

